5... O-O 6. O-O d5
{ This is perhaps the most principled attempt at equalizing against our venomous Italian. Black wants to occupy the center, using the fact that White himself has chosen a slower plan of not going for the quick d3-d4.  This ambitious plan of Black, however, also has some significant drawbacks: the ...d7-d5-break costs a tempo, the knight on d5 will be temporarily exposed and the e5-pawn is now a target, with the rook being able to hit it along the semi-open e-file. And very importantly, the c6-knight is still a bad piece restricted by the c3-pawn; the break in the center doesn't address that issue. }
7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1
{ The most popular, natural and in my opinion also the most testing of the options.   Alternatively, the cunning move  8.a4!?  is also a venomous one. }
8... Be6
{ This has once been played by Anand against Kramnik in a rapid game.   The trick is that the e5-pawn is not actually hanging because after  9.Nxe5?  Nxe5  10.Rxe5  there is  10...Bxf2+!  11.Kxf2  Qf6+!  ,  which is a common theme in these positions. In fact, the threat is stronger than the execution so we just keep our eyes on the e5-pawn and continue developing. }
9. Nbd2
{ White reinforces the Nxe5 threat. The same ...Qf6+ trick would no longer work because of Nf3, protecting the rook on e5:   9...--  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  Bxf2+??  12.Kxf2  Qf6+  13.Nf3+-  . }
9... Bd6 10. a4
{ A very clever improvement on Kramnik's play. White's development scheme in this structure is generally Ne4, b2-b4, a2-a4 and a4-a5, grabbing space on the queenside and while Kramnik started with the natural Ne4 followed by b2-b4, the computer comes up with a much more sophisticated move order.  If we start with a4-a5 first, we create a nasty threat of Qb3 @@StartBracket@@as the ...Na5! idea is dealt with@@EndBracket@@ and after Black protects against it with a useless move like ...Rb8, only then do we proceed with Ne4 and b2-b4, gaining that small tempo on the way. Very nice! }
10... Re8 11. a5 { Now that ...Na5 is prevented, Qb3 is a real threat. } 11...
Rb8
{ A useless move, in general, but here it was necessary to guard the b7-pawn against Qb3. }
12. Ne4
{ Now we proceed with the standard development scheme. The knight not only is active on the e4-square, but it also guards the c3-pawn, so our b-pawn can advance. }
12... h6 { Black has to prevent Ng5. } 13. b4 a6
{ Stopping White's expansion, but the deadlock that we have established on the queenside is to our advantage. In the long term, the b7-pawn is weak, and Black's queenside is cramped. }
14. Qb3 { Upping the pressure. } 14... Nf6 15. Be3
{ We have finished our development comfortably. Black can simplify, but he can't equalize. }
15... Nxe4
{ This trade is not solving the issue of the inferiority of Black's queenside pawn structure and the bad c6-knight. }
16. dxe4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4
{ This is one kind of position we are often aiming for in the slow Italian. Although there is some symmetry, all the minor imbalances in the position are in White's favor. We have a better bishop, a better knight and a better pawn structure on the queenside.  Next up we want to slightly improve our kingside with g2-g3+Kg2 and perhaps double on the d-file, before taking further actions. Also, the f3-knight is always ready to embark on journeys, usually via d2 to c4 or b3-c5. }
