{ A typical move in this variation. Black removes the vulnerable d5-knight with a tempo. Now it is a big moment for White. }
10. h3
{ First we include this push, kicking the bishop away to h5, which is where we want the bishop to be in this particular line @@StartBracket@@note that we waited with this h3-push, until Black has shown his cards with 9...Nb6@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bh5 { The retreat is the most natural and is the way they play. } 11. Bb3
{ This was an epic idea first shown to me by my teammate Jorden van Foreest. It turns out that capturing the d3-pawn leads to some complications and more importantly, these complications seem to lead to unpleasant positions for Black.  By now there are a few dozen high-level games on this topic and there is still no consensus on how exactly Black is supposed to neutralize White's initiative. First Black has to choose, to capture the pawn or not to. }
11... Qxd3 { Capturing the pawn is the most direct way to go. } 12. Nxe5
{ The complications are clearly about to start. Black is once again facing a tough choice: does he want to sit it out in a worse endgame after  12...Bxd1  , retreat with  12...Qf5  or try his luck with the crazy-looking  12...Qg3  ?. }
12... Qf5
