{ Here it is a novelty, but obviously, since I played the same concept against Ba7, it doesn't really count as such. The idea is again to protect the e4-pawn. Unfortunately, we are not able to do it with the b1-knight and must resort to finesses. }
11... Re8 12. Bc2
{ The pawns are protected. Black has a choice now: to give up the fight for the central squares and go for the bishop pair or to keep the tension. }
12... exd4 { The tempting reaction, to go for the bishop, with ...Nb4 next. }
13. cxd4 Nb4 14. Nc3
{ We are happy with our pawn center and our knights protecting it beautifully. We are sad to see our c2-bishop go, but you can't have it all, if the opponent is not a complete noob. }
14... Nxc2 15. Qxc2
{ Whether the bishop is on b6 or a7, I believe the nature of the position is the same. White just wants to get the c1-bishop and the a1-rook towards the center, while Black is hoping to stir up some action before White mobilizes his forces fully. }
15... d5
