1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Be7
{ This is traditionally the main alternative to the much more common ...Bc5-setups. Black develops more modestly here, going for a passive but very solid setup.  It occurs quite a bit across all levels and even at the very top, from time to time, it shows up. Recently, it has been played a lot by Daniil Dubov and before him Richard Rapport, not to mention that even Magnus Carlsen has used this system occasionally. }
5. O-O O-O
{ Black can also start with  5...d6  , this move order is testing our basic understanding of the Italian structures and creates a thematic position threat of ...Na5.  6.a4   This is the right move order, as  6.Nc3  allows  6...Na5  .  6...O-O  What else?  7.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppppbppp/2n2n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  6.Nc3  d6  7.a4  . }
6. Nc3
{ The old main line is  6.Re1  , but these days it is also trendy to develop the knight here.  I think the main reason why the Nc3-setup is more promising here than against the ...Bc5-setups is that the situation around the d4-square control is quite different.  With the bishop not being on c5, ...Nd4 is not on the cards and at the same time, White can gain further control over the d4-square with an h3+Be3-setup. }
6... d6
{ There doesn't appear to be any point in postponing the ...d6-push.   The move  6...h6  is not too bad, but with ...d6 happening next, it will just transpose back into 6...d6 after  7.a4  d6  - see 6...d6 7.a4 h6. }
7. a4
{ White needs to address the threat of ...Na5.   I had played  7.a3  , which is similar, but finally, I chose to recommend this push, grabbing more space on the queenside.  This is a huge tabia, as Black has a lot of different ideas and move orders here. }
7... Be6
{ This is a common idea in this system. Black offers a trade of bishops, willing to double his pawns in return for potential counterplay along the f-file.  With the knight being on c3, we generally respond with Nd5!, as trading on e6 would mean that our control of the d5-square vanishes and there is then little purpose to the knight being on c3.   With that in mind, though,  8.Bxe6  fxe6  9.Ne2!  , followed by Ng3 is definitely a possibility as well. }
8. Nd5
{ As we can see in this chapter, this is the standard way of responding to ...Be6.  Black can't recapture with the knight as it loses a piece to the exd5 fork while recapturing with the bishop gives up the bishop pair. }
8... Bxd5
{ The most principled, otherwise we go c2-c3 next and get excellent control of the center. }
9. exd5 Nb4
{ Black is targeting our weak d5-pawn, but we have a strong follow up in  10.d4!  . }
10. d4
{ Trying to reconnect with our d5-pawn and ready to embrace the complications. }
10... Nbxd5
{ This leads to a small plus for White, thanks to the bishop pair in a very simple and pretty symmetrical pawn structure. }
11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nxe5
{ With the position being very open, thanks to a very clear board and no pawns left in the center, Black doesn't have much in return for our bishop pair.  Black remains very solid, but I believe this is enough for us to claim a small plus. }
